&gt; The fail(Throwable) throws a subclass of AssertionFailedError that 
&gt; supports chained exceptions: so that you won&#39;t loose one bit of the 
&gt; stacktrace.  So please, please no more &quot;fail(e.getMessage())&quot;!

I use this to specifically test for exceptions. If I want to test 
whether my FooFileLoader throws an FileNotFoundException, I do the 
following, instead of letting the framework handle the exception as 
an error. I think it is just a matter of definition of what consists 
of a failure of your requirement (in this case the contract of the 
FooFileLoader) or an error.

testFileNotFound(){
    try{
        FooFileLoader f = new FooFileLoader( &quot;unknownfile.txt&quot; );
        fail( &quot;FileNotFoundException expected, got none&quot; );
    } catch( FileNotFoundException e ){
        // success!
    } catch( Exception e ){
        fail( &quot;FileNotFoundException expected, caught: &quot; + e );
    }
}

